DataElement.preferredName: Fibroblast Growth Factor Receptor 1 Messenger RNA in situ Hybridization Assessment Score
DataElement.preferredDefinition: The response used to represent the effectiveness of the evaluation of mRNA to detect the presence of complementary sequences of Fibroblast Growth Factor Receptor 1 utilizing in-situ hybridization techniques.

DataElementConcept.preferredName: Fibroblast Growth Factor Receptor 1 Messenger RNA in situ Hybridization Assessment
DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: Acidic fibroblast growth factor stimulates tyrosine kinase activity of FGFR1, the receptor for acidic FGF.  The receptor is a transmembrane protein that contains three extracellular Ig-like domains, an unusual acidic region, and an intracellular tyrosine kinase domain.  (from OMIM 136350 and NCI)_A class of RNA molecule containing protein-coding information in its nucleotide sequence that can be translated into the amino acid sequence of a protein._Use of a DNA or RNA probe to detect the presence of complementary sequences in chromosomes, cells, or tissues_Having determined the value, significance, or extent of.

Concepts.definition: Fibroblast growth factor receptor 1 (822 aa, ~92 kDa) is encoded by the human FGFR1 gene. This protein is involved in the regulation of embryonic development, cell proliferation, cell differentiation and cellular migration.
A class of RNA molecule containing protein-coding information in its nucleotide sequence that can be translated into the amino acid sequence of a protein.
Use of a DNA or RNA probe to detect the presence of complementary sequences in chromosomes, cells, or tissues.
